## **8. Challenges and Solutions**

| Challenge | Solution | Outcome |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| Calculating correct octal value for target permissions | Used the binary-to-octal table: each permission group is a 3-bit binary number — 7=111=rwx, 6=110=rw-, 0=000=--- | Correctly computed `760` for the target permission set |
| Understanding why `chown` requires `sudo` | Regular users can only change ownership of files they own; `sudo` is required to change ownership of files owned by other users or system processes | Used `sudo chown -R` for all ownership changes |
| Distinguishing symbolic `u` from absolute octal | Symbolic mode uses letter references (`u`=user, `g`=group, `o`=others) with `+/-/=` operators; absolute mode uses a three-digit octal number | Applied correct syntax for each mode in the respective tasks |
| Verifying recursive ownership change applied to all files | Used `ls -lR` on the target directory to check ownership strings on subdirectories and files | Confirmed all entries showed the new owner:group values |

